{"@context":"https:\/\/schema.org\/","@type":"NewsArticle","@id":"https:\/\/cyble.com\/blog\/under-the-lens-eagle-monitor-rat\/#newsarticle","url":"https:\/\/cyble.com\/blog\/under-the-lens-eagle-monitor-rat\/","headline":"Cyble - Under the lens: Eagle Monitor RAT","mainEntityOfPage":"https:\/\/cyble.com\/blog\/under-the-lens-eagle-monitor-rat\/","datePublished":"2022-04-18T08:53:05-04:00","dateModified":"2025-02-10T06:55:32-05:00","description":"Cyble looks at the recently resurfaced Eagle Monitor RAT and the new TTPs encountered in this iteration of the popular RAT.","articleSection":"Trojan","articleBody":"A Remote Administration Tool is a type of software that gives the attacker full control over the victims' device remotely. Using RATs, attackers can perform various tasks such as accessing files, cameras, and other resources remotely while conducting keylogging, system operations, etc.    A developer named \"Arsium\" posted a new version of this open-source RAT \u2013 EagleMonitorRAT - on GitHub. Additionally, the developer posted a link to the GitHub page of the EagleMonitorRAT to various underground dark web markets. Figure 1 shows one such post by the developer.    Figure 1 - Post by EagleMonitorRAT Developer        According to the developer, the EagleMonitorRAT is written in C# and upgraded from HorusEyesRat, which is Visual Basic .NET-based.    Cyble Research Labs has analyzed the RAT binary and panel to gain insights into the functionalities and impact of the RAT.    RAT Details        While building the solution, &nbsp;various executables and support plugins are compiled, including client builder plugins and an admin panel. Figure 2 shows the compiled binaries and other files.    Figure 2 - Compiled Binaries for EagleMonitorRAT        Additionally, various Dynamic Link Library (DLL) files are also compiled to support operations such as file management, keylogging, etc. Figure 3 shows the support DLL files.    Figure 3 - List of DLL Files after compilation        A client builder is used to compile the binary, which will be delivered to users to compromise a target machine. The client binary may be delivered to users using various initial infection vectors such as spam email etc. The builder has an option to specify the IP address of the server, port, and key. Figure 4 shows the client builder.    Figure 4 - EagleMonitorRAT Client Builder Panel        EagleMonitorRAT has a server panel for managing victim devices. The panel shows country, hardware ID, operating system details, username, available RAM, privilege, region etc. Additionally, the panel has various options to manage as well for performing several operations in the infected device.    The Admin panel of EagleMonitorRAT includes operations such as:     recovery    desktop    miscellaneous panels    mass tasks    memory execution    information    client     Figure 5 shows the administration panel of EagleMonitorRAT.    Figure 5 - Administration Panel of EagleMonitorRAT        In the recovery option of EagleMonitorRAT, there are three different options - passwords, history, and autofill.    The Recovery option works as an information stealer which extracts usernames, passwords, and browser history. Figure 6 shows stolen information retrieved using the Recovery menu from the victim's machine.    Figure 6 - Recovery Data extracted from the Recovery Option        The Desktop menu option of EagleMonitorRAT has 5 different suboperations - file manager, process manager, live keylogger, remote desktop, and remote webcam. Refer to Figure 7.    Figure 7 - Desktop Option of EagleMonitorRAT        The File Manager menu option of EagleMonitorRAT gives TAs the functionality to manage files in the specific directory of the infected device, as shown below.    Figure 8 - File Manager Option of the RAT        The Process Manager menu options show the details of the running process of the infected device, such as Icon, ID, Name, Window Title, Window Handle, and Is64Bit. Figure 9 shows the Process Manager.    Figure 9 - Process Manager of the EagleMonitorRAT        The shellcode injection menu option of the EagleMonitorRAT gives attackers an option to perform shellcode injection remotely in the infected device. Refer to Figure 10.    Figure 10 - Remote Shellcode Injection Option        The EagleMonitorRAT has a live keylogger functionality to remotely capture the victim system's keystrokes. Figure 11 shows the keylogger menu operation of the RAT.    Figure 11 - Live Keylogger        The Remote Desktop functionality captures screenshots of the victim system remotely at predefined intervals. Figure 12 shows the captured screen.    Figure 12 - Screenshot Captured by the EagleMonitorRAT        This RAT has a menu option to remotely capture the webcam feed of the infected system as well. Figure 13 shows the webcam panel.    Figure 13 - Webcam Panel of the EagleMonitorRAT        The EagleMonitorRAT has miscellaneous menu options to perform other remote operations such as hiding the taskbar, changing wallpapers, sound management, etc., as shown below.    Figure 14 - Miscellaneous Options of EagleMonitorRAT        EagleMonitorRAT also has a menu option to discover the network connection and get the CPU information of the infected system. Figure 15 shows the network connection and CPU information.    Figure 15 - Network connection and CPU Monitoring        The RAT panel has a menu option to remotely shutdown, reboot, log out, BSOD, lock the workstation, hibernate and suspend the victim's system. Figure 16 showcases these options.    Figure 16 - Remote Client Management Option        Conclusion        RATs have steadily become stealthier and more efficient with new techniques in place. Various cybercriminals and Advanced Persistent Threat Groups have leveraged RATs in the past.    Cyble has observed data breaches in high-profile organizations due to such threats. Since EagleMonitor is an open-source RAT, it is possible that threat actors could create and deploy custom variations for future attacks. Organizations and individuals should thus continue to follow industry best cybersecurity practices.    Our Recommendations:&nbsp;         Use strong passwords and enforce multi-factor authentication wherever possible.\u00a0\u00a0    Turn on the automatic software update feature on your computer, mobile, and other connected devices.\u00a0      Use a reputed anti-virus and internet security software package on your connected devices, including PC, laptop, and mobile.\u00a0    Refrain from opening untrusted links and email attachments without first verifying their authenticity.\u00a0\u00a0    Educate employees in terms of protecting themselves from threats like phishing's\/untrusted URLs.\u00a0    Block URLs that could be used to spread the malware, e.g., Torrent\/Warez.\u00a0    Monitor the beacon on the network level to block data exfiltration by malware or TAs.\u00a0    Enable Data Loss Prevention (DLP) Solutions on the employees' systems.\u00a0     MITRE ATT&amp;CK\u00ae Techniques\u202f&nbsp;        Tactic&nbsp;Technique ID&nbsp;Technique Name&nbsp;Execution\u202f&nbsp;T1204&nbsp;User Execution&nbsp;Privilege EscalationT1543T1055Create or Modify System ProcessProcess InjectionCredential Access&nbsp;T1555&nbsp;T1539&nbsp; T1552&nbsp; T1528&nbsp;Credentials from Password Stores&nbsp; Steal Web Session Cookie&nbsp; Unsecured Credentials&nbsp; Steal Application Access Token&nbsp;Collection&nbsp;T1113&nbsp; T1123 T1119 T1005 T1056Screen Capture&nbsp; Audio Capture Automated Collection Data from Local System Input CaptureDiscovery&nbsp;T1518&nbsp; T1124&nbsp; T1007&nbsp; T1083 T1046Software Discovery&nbsp; System Time data-widget_type="theme-post-title.default"> <div class="elementor-widget-container"> <h1 class="elementor-heading-title elementor-size-default">Under the lens: Eagle Monitor RAT</h1> </div> </div> <div class="elementor-element elementor-element-1fcc1d6c elementor-widget elementor-widget-theme-post-excerpt" data-id="1fcc1d6c" data-element_type="widget" data-widget_type="theme-post-excerpt.default"> <div class="elementor-widget-container"> Cyble looks at the recently resurfaced Eagle Monitor RAT and the new TTPs encountered in this iteration of the popular RAT. </div> </div> <div class="elementor-element elementor-element-2907e1e2 blog_content elementor-widget elementor-widget-theme-post-content" data-id="2907e1e2" data-element_type="widget" data-widget_type="theme-post-content.default"> <div class="elementor-widget-container"> <p>A Remote Administration Tool is a type of software that gives the attacker full control over the victims&#8217; device remotely. Using RATs, attackers can perform various tasks such as accessing files, cameras, and other resources remotely while conducting keylogging, system operations, etc.</p><p>A developer named &#8220;Arsium&#8221; <a href="https://github.com/arsium/EagleMonitorRAT" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">posted</a> a new version of this open-source RAT – EagleMonitorRAT &#8211; on GitHub. Additionally, the developer posted a link to the GitHub page of the EagleMonitorRAT to various underground dark web markets. Figure 1 shows one such post by the developer.</p><figure class="wp-block-image aligncenter size-large"><img width="1024" height="646" data-attachment-id="10566" data-permalink="https://cyble.com/blog/under-the-lens-eagle-monitor-rat/figure-1-post-by-eaglemonitorrat-developer/" data-orig-file="https://cyble.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/Figure-1-Post-by-EagleMonitorRAT-Developer.png" data-orig-size="1026,647" data-comments-opened="0" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Figure-1-Post-by-EagleMonitorRAT-Developer" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://cyble.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/Figure-1-Post-by-EagleMonitorRAT-Developer-300x189.png" data-large-file="https://cyble.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/Figure-1-Post-by-EagleMonitorRAT-Developer-1024x646.png" alt="RAT" title="Under the lens: Eagle Monitor RAT 17" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" nitro-lazy-srcset="https://cdn-khlfb.nitrocdn.com/JPtKKXLsjJbtelUWnenRbIbVJOerqPTK/assets/images/optimized/rev-717c118/cyble.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/Figure-1-Post-by-EagleMonitorRAT-Developer-1024x646.png 1024w, https://cdn-khlfb.nitrocdn.com/JPtKKXLsjJbtelUWnenRbIbVJOerqPTK/assets/images/optimized/rev-717c118/cyble.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/Figure-1-Post-by-EagleMonitorRAT-Developer-600x378.png 600w, https://cdn-khlfb.nitrocdn.com/JPtKKXLsjJbtelUWnenRbIbVJOerqPTK/assets/images/optimized/rev-717c118/cyble.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/Figure-1-Post-by-EagleMonitorRAT-Developer-300x189.png 300w, https://cdn-khlfb.nitrocdn.com/JPtKKXLsjJbtelUWnenRbIbVJOerqPTK/assets/images/optimized/rev-717c118/cyble.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/Figure-1-Post-by-EagleMonitorRAT-Developer-768x484.png 768w, https://cdn-khlfb.nitrocdn.com/JPtKKXLsjJbtelUWnenRbIbVJOerqPTK/assets/images/optimized/rev-717c118/cyble.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/Figure-1-Post-by-EagleMonitorRAT-Developer.png 1026w" nitro-lazy-src="https://cdn-khlfb.nitrocdn.com/JPtKKXLsjJbtelUWnenRbIbVJOerqPTK/assets/images/optimized/rev-717c118/cyble.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/Figure-1-Post-by-EagleMonitorRAT-Developer-1024x646.png" class="wp-image-10566 nitro-lazy" decoding="async" nitro-lazy-empty src="data:image/svg+xml;base64,PHN2ZyB2aWV3Qm94PSIwIDAgMTAyNCA2NDYiIHdpZHRoPSIxMDI0IiBoZWlnaHQ9IjY0NiIgeG1sbnM9Imh0dHA6Ly93d3cudzMub3JnLzIwMDAvc3ZnIj48L3N2Zz4=" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Figure 1 &#8211; Post by EagleMonitorRAT Developer</figcaption></figure><p></p> <div id="om-wlravxmwms40sunr2q0v-holder"></div> <template data-nitro-marker-id="a63c15a9ea9c95cbcf4be387544881a9-1"></template> <p>According to the developer, the EagleMonitorRAT is written in C# and upgraded from HorusEyesRat, which is Visual Basic .NET-based.</p><p>Cyble Research Labs has analyzed the RAT binary and panel to gain insights into the functionalities and impact of the RAT.</p><h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-rat-details">RAT Details</h2><p></p><p>While building the solution, &nbsp;various executables and support plugins are compiled, including client builder plugins and an admin panel. Figure 2 shows the compiled binaries and other files.</p><figure class="wp-block-image aligncenter size-full"><img width="285" height="321" data-attachment-id="10567" data-permalink="https://cyble.com/blog/under-the-lens-eagle-monitor-rat/figure-2-compiled-binaries-for-eaglemonitor-rat/" data-orig-file="https://cyble.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/Figure-2-Compiled-Binaries-for-EagleMonitor-RAT.png" data-orig-size="285,321" data-comments-opened="0" 266w" nitro-lazy-src="https://cdn-khlfb.nitrocdn.com/JPtKKXLsjJbtelUWnenRbIbVJOerqPTK/assets/images/optimized/rev-717c118/cyble.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/Figure-2-Compiled-Binaries-for-EagleMonitor-RAT.png" class="wp-image-10567 nitro-lazy" decoding="async" nitro-lazy-empty class="wp-element-caption">Figure 2 &#8211; Compiled Binaries for EagleMonitorRAT</figcaption></figure><p></p><p>Additionally, various Dynamic Link Library (DLL) files are also compiled to support operations such as file management, keylogging, etc. Figure 3 shows the support DLL files.</p><div class="cyble-content_6" id="cyble-977268675"><div style="position:relative;padding-bottom:15%;height:0;height:auto;overflow:hidden;max-width:100%;">  <a href="https://cyble.com/request-demo/?utm_source=cril&utm_medium=mid" target="_blank" the video tag. </video> </div> </div><figure class="wp-block-image aligncenter size-full"><img width="271" height="368" data-attachment-id="10568" nitro-lazy-src="https://cdn-khlfb.nitrocdn.com/JPtKKXLsjJbtelUWnenRbIbVJOerqPTK/assets/images/optimized/rev-717c118/cyble.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/Figure-3-List-of-DLL-Files-after-compilation.png" src="data:image/svg+xml;base64,PHN2ZyB2aWV3Qm94PSIwIDAgMjcxIDM2OCIgd2lkdGg9IjI3MSIgaGVpZ2h0PSIzNjgiIHhtbG5zPSJodHRwOi8vd3d3LnczLm9yZy8yMDAwL3N2ZyI+PC9zdmc+" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Figure 3 &#8211; List of DLL Files after compilation</figcaption></figure><p></p><p>A client builder is used to compile the binary, which will be delivered to users to compromise a target machine. The client binary may be delivered to users using various initial infection vectors such as spam email etc. The builder has an option to specify the IP address of the server, port, and key. Figure 4 shows the client builder.</p><figure class="wp-block-image aligncenter size-full"><img width="740" height="474" data-attachment-id="10569" data-permalink="https://cyble.com/blog/under-the-lens-eagle-monitor-rat/figure-4-eaglemonitorrat-client-builder-panel/" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" 740w, https://cdn-khlfb.nitrocdn.com/JPtKKXLsjJbtelUWnenRbIbVJOerqPTK/assets/images/optimized/rev-717c118/cyble.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/Figure-4-EagleMonitorRAT-Client-Builder-Panel-600x384.png 300w" nitro-lazy-src="https://cdn-khlfb.nitrocdn.com/JPtKKXLsjJbtelUWnenRbIbVJOerqPTK/assets/images/optimized/rev-717c118/cyble.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/Figure-4-EagleMonitorRAT-Client-Builder-Panel.png" class="wp-image-10569 nitro-lazy" decoding="async" nitro-lazy-empty src="data:image/svg+xml;base64,PHN2ZyB2aWV3Qm94PSIwIDAgNzQwIDQ3NCIgd2lkdGg9Ijc0MCIgaGVpZ2h0PSI0NzQiIHhtbG5zPSJodHRwOi8vd3d3LnczLm9yZy8yMDAwL3N2ZyI+PC9zdmc+" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Figure 4 &#8211; EagleMonitorRAT Client Builder Panel</figcaption></figure><p></p><p>EagleMonitorRAT has a server panel for managing victim devices. The panel shows country, hardware ID, operating system details, username, available RAM, privilege, region etc. Additionally, the panel has various options to manage as well for performing several operations in the infected device.</p><p>The Admin panel of EagleMonitorRAT includes operations such as:</p><ul class="wp-block-list"><li>recovery</li> <li>desktop</li> <li>miscellaneous panels</li> <li>mass tasks</li> <li>memory execution</li> <li>information</li> <li>client</li></ul><p>Figure 5 shows the administration panel of EagleMonitorRAT.</p><figure class="wp-block-image aligncenter class="wp-element-caption">Figure 5 &#8211; Administration Panel of EagleMonitorRAT</figcaption></figure><p></p><p>In the recovery option of EagleMonitorRAT, there are three different options &#8211; passwords, history, and autofill.</p><p>The Recovery option works as an information stealer which extracts usernames, passwords, and browser history. Figure 6 shows stolen information retrieved using the Recovery menu from the victim&#8217;s machine.</p><figure class="wp-block-image aligncenter size-full"><img width="803" height="449" class="wp-element-caption">Figure 11 &#8211; Live Keylogger</figcaption></figure><p></p><p>The Remote Desktop functionality captures screenshots of the victim system remotely at predefined intervals. class="wp-element-caption">Figure 16 &#8211; Remote Client Management Option</figcaption></figure><p></p><h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-conclusion">Conclusion</h2><p></p><p>RATs have steadily become stealthier and more efficient with new techniques in place. Various cybercriminals and Advanced Persistent Threat Groups have leveraged RATs in the past.</p><p>Cyble has observed data breaches in high-profile organizations due to such threats. Since EagleMonitor is an open-source RAT, it is possible that threat actors could create and deploy custom variations for future attacks. Organizations and individuals should thus continue to follow industry best cybersecurity practices.</p><h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-our-recommendations">Our Recommendations:&nbsp;</h2><p></p><ul class="wp-block-list"><li>Use strong passwords and enforce multi-factor authentication wherever possible.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li> <li>Turn on the automatic software update feature on your computer, mobile, and other connected devices.&nbsp;</li></ul><ul class="wp-block-list"><li>Use a reputed anti-virus and internet security software package on your connected devices, including PC, laptop, and mobile.&nbsp;</li> <li>Refrain from opening untrusted links and email attachments without first verifying their authenticity.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li> <li>Educate employees in terms of protecting themselves from threats like phishing&#8217;s/untrusted URLs.&nbsp;</li> <li>Block URLs that could be used to spread the malware, e.g., Torrent/Warez.&nbsp;</li> <li>Monitor the beacon on the network level to block data exfiltration by malware or TAs.&nbsp;</li> <li>Enable Data Loss Prevention (DLP) Solutions on the employees&#8217; systems.&nbsp;</li></ul><h2 class="wp-block-heading">MITRE ATT&amp;CK® Techniques &nbsp;</h2><p></p><figure class="wp-block-table"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Tactic&nbsp;</strong></td><td><strong>Technique ID&nbsp;</strong><strong></strong></td><td><strong>Technique
